[[Image:Shandwick Reverse.jpg|thumb|Reverse, landward side. This is a 19th-century illustration.]] [[File:Shandwick02.jpg|thumb|Clach a' Charridh, Landward side]] The '''Clach a' Charridh''' or '''Shandwick Stone''' is a Class II [[Pictish stones|Pictish stone]] located near [[Shandwick]] on the [[Tarbat peninsula]] in [[Easter Ross]], [[Scotland]].
[[Image:Scotland Highlands Shandwick Stone.jpg|thumb|250px|left]] ==Carving== It is a Class II stone, with the [[cross]] facing the seaward side, and the secular scene facing inland.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://her.highland.gov.uk/SingleResult.aspx?uid=%27MHG8539%27| title=The Shandwick Stone| publisher=Highland Council: Historic Environment Record| accessdate=18 October 2009}}</ref> The latter contains six panels, the first (from top to bottom) being a standard Pictish double-disc, the second being a [[Pictish Beast]] and the third being a possible hunting scene, with warriors depicted alongside an eagle, a boar, and various other creatures. The bottom three panels consist of woven patterns. The stone is now encased in a glass cover room.
==History== The Gaelic name (''Clach a’ Charaidh'') means ‘stone of the grave-plots’. A burial ground here was recorded in 1889 as last used during the cholera epidemic of 1832 and ploughed under about 1885.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://her.highland.gov.uk/SingleResult.aspx?uid='THG7'| title=The Pictish Trail| publisher=Highland Council: Historic Environment Record| accessdate=18 October 2009}}</ref>
