{{Infobox Politician | name = Indira Naidoo-Harris | image = Indira Naidoo-Harris - 2017 (cropped).jpg | caption = Naidoo-Harris in 2017 | office1 = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|Ontario MPP]] | term_start1 = 2014 | term_end1 = 2018 | predecessor1 = [[Ted Chudleigh]] | successor1 = [[Parm Gill]] | constituency1 = [[Halton (provincial electoral district)|Halton]] | party = [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal Party]] | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Durban, South Africa]] | residence = [[Milton, Ontario]] | profession = Journalist | spouse = Randy Harris | children = 2 }} '''Indira Naidoo-Harris''' is a former politician in [[Ontario]], Canada. She was a [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal]] member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] from 2014 to 2018 who represented the riding of [[Halton (provincial electoral district)|Halton]]. She served as a cabinet minister in the government of [[Kathleen Wynne]]. She was the [[Ministry of Education (Ontario)|Minister of Education]], and the Minister responsible for Early Years and Child Care.
==Background== Naidoo-Harris was born in Durban [[South Africa]] under Apartheid. She immigrated to Canada as a child, and grew up in [[Alberta]]. She graduated from the [[University of Lethbridge]] and spent her early broadcasting career with [[NBC]] and [[PBS]] before moving to [[Ontario]] in the 1990s.<ref>http://news.ontario.ca/profiles/en/indira-naidoo-harris</ref>
Prior to the election, she was a [[CBC Radio]] newsreader and a [[CBC Television]] journalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-votes-2014/ontario-election-2014-seat-changes-highlight-election-night-surprises-1.2674219 |title=Ontario election 2014: Seat changes highlight election night surprises |date=June 13, 2014 |publisher=CBC News |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6QK5Mqlns?url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-votes-2014/ontario-election-2014-seat-changes-highlight-election-night-surprises-1.2674219 |archivedate=June 14, 2014 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> She lives in [[Milton, Ontario]] with her husband Randy and their two children.<ref>{{cite news |title=Indira Naidoo-Harris plans public service entry |last=Rao |first=Sunil |newspaper=South Asian Focus |location=Brampton, Ont |date=November 24, 2010 |page=1}}</ref>
==Politics== Naidoo-Harris ran in the [[Ontario general election, 2011|2011 provincial election]] as the [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal]] candidate in the riding of [[Halton (provincial electoral district)|Halton]]. She was defeated by [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Progressive Conservative]] incumbent [[Ted Chudleigh]] by 3,148 votes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thespec.com/news-story/4575769-chudleigh-looking-for-third-election-win/ |title=15-year Tory rein in Halton halted by Liberal |last=Beattie |first=Samantha |date=June 13, 2014 |newspaper=The Hamilton Spectator |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6QK5fgwyv?url=http://www.thespec.com/news-story/4575769-chudleigh-looking-for-third-election-win/ |archivedate=June 14, 2014 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref><ref name="2011 results">{{cite web|url=http://elections.on.ca/NR/rdonlyres/7849B894-4C4F-490E-9E8C-271BCF0C0D4D/5712/SummaryofvalidvotescastforeacndGE2011.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330163815/http://elections.on.ca/NR/rdonlyres/7849B894-4C4F-490E-9E8C-271BCF0C0D4D/5712/SummaryofvalidvotescastforeacndGE2011.pdf |dead-url=yes |archive-date=March 30, 2013 |format=PDF |title=Summary of Valid Ballots Cast for Each Candidate |publisher=Elections Ontario |date=October 6, 2011 |accessdate=2014-03-02 |page=6 }}</ref> She ran again in the [[Ontario general election, 2014|2014 election]] against Chudleigh this time defeating him by 5,726 votes.<ref name="2014 results">{{cite web |title=General Election by District: Halton |publisher=Elections Ontario |date=June 12, 2014 |url=http://wemakevotingeasy.ca/en/general-election-district-results.aspx?d=030}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Slaughter|first=Graham|title=Liberal candidate Indira Naidoo-Harris wins Halton in Ontario election|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/ontario_election/riding_profiles/2014/06/12/liberal_candidate_indira_naidooharris_wins_halton_in_ontario_election.html|accessdate=June 13, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=June 12, 2014}}</ref>
From 2014 to 2016 she was a [[Parliamentary Assistant]] to the [[Minister of Health and Long-Term Care (Ontario)|Minister of Health and Long-Term Care]]. On June 13, 2016, she was named Associate Minister of Finance Responsible for the Ontario Retirement Pension Plan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Halton MPP Indira Naidoo-Harris named associate finance minister |url=http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/6720060-halton-mpp-indira-naidoo-harris-named-associate-finance-minister |first=Melanie |last=Hennessey |date=June 13, 2016 |newspaper=Inside Halton |publisher=Metroland Media}}</ref><ref name="2016WynneCab">{{cite news |title=Kathleen Wynne's shuffled cabinet features 40% women |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-cabinet-changes-1.3632476 |publisher=CBC News |date=June 13, 2016}}</ref> On August 24, 2016 she was transferred from the pension role to a new educational ministerial position responsible for early year education and child care.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wynne taps Naidoo-Harris to be early years and child care minister |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2016/08/24/wynne-taps-naidoo-harris-to-be-early-years-and-child-care-minister.html |last=Benzie |first=Robert |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=August 24, 2016}}</ref> In addition to her role as Minister Responsible for Early Years and Child Care, in January 2017, Minister Naidoo-Harris was also named [[Ministry of the Status of Women (Ontario)|Minister of the Status of Women]]. In January 2018, she was named [[Ministry of Education (Ontario)|Minister of Education]] and kept her role as Minister Responsible for Early Years and Child Care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/profiles/en/indira-naidoo-harris|title=Newsroom : Biography : Indira Naidoo-Harris|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref>
Naidoo-Harris was nominated to run for re-election as the Liberal candidate for the newly formed riding of Milton but was defeated in the ensuing election.
==Personal== Naidoo-Harris is married and has two children. She moved to Ontario in the 1990s to work for CBC-TV’s The National and Midday News, and since then she has anchored for CBC, CTV, TVO and OMNI Television. Naidoo-Harris has won numerous awards for her work and volunteerism in national and international causes.
