{{Infobox person | name = Margaret Alberta Armen | image = <!--just the name, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Margaret Alberta Sampsell | birth_date = {{Birth date|1921|9|9}} | birth_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S. | death_date = {{Death date and age|2003|11|10|1921|9|9}} | death_place = [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]], California, U.S. | death_cause = | resting_place = [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park, Hollywood Hills]] | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | other_names = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of California]] | occupation = [[Screenwriter]], author | years_active = 1960–1984 | spouse = Garo Armen | children = 1 | parents = | relatives = | awards = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> }}
'''Margaret Alberta Armen'''<ref name="ObitNotice">{{cite news |url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/latimes/obituary.aspx?pid=1600888 |title=Obituary: Armen, Margaret Alberta |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 14, 2003 |accessdate=February 2, 2017}}</ref> (September 9, 1921 – November 10, 2003) was an American screenwriter and author.
==Biography== She was born Margaret Alberta Sampsell in [[Washington, D.C.]],<ref name="cowboydirectory">{{cite web |url=http://www.cowboydirectory.com/A/a__ara.html |title=Page A – 4 (Aranda to Arthur) |year=2003 |first=Stan |last=Paregien, Sr. |work=Cowboy Directory |accessdate=February 2, 2017}}</ref> the daughter of [[Commander (United States)|Commander]] Thomas Lloyd Sampsell and Florence Neilson (née Buehler).{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} Her father was a [[dental surgeon]] serving in the [[United States Navy Dental Corps]],<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/registerofcommis1918wash#page/160/mode/2up/search/Sampsell |title=Register of the Commissioned and Warrant Officers of the United States Navy and U. S. Naval Reserve Force, National Naval Volunteers, Marine Corps, Medical Reserve Corps and Dental Reserve Corps |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[Government Printing Office]] |date=January 1, 1918 |page=160 |accessdate=February 2, 2017}}</ref> and she grew up in [[Manila]], [[Panama]], [[Japan]], and spent four years living in [[Peking]], China, where she learned [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]].<ref name="cowboydirectory"/>
She graduated with a degree in [[English literature]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]], then studied [[creative writing]] at [[University of California, Los Angeles]]. On June 30, 1945, she married Garo Armen, a naval officer,<ref name="cowboydirectory"/> and started a family. While raising her son, she worked from home, writing newspaper articles and short stories, before finally breaking into television<ref name="Cushman">{{cite book |url=http://trekkiefeminist.tumblr.com/post/105924981927/writer-margaret-armen-was-the-daughter-of-a-naval |title=These Are The Voyages – TOS: Season 2 |first=Marc |last=Cushman |authorlink=Marc Cushman |location=Los Angeles |publisher=Jacobs/Brown Press |year=2014 |isbn=978-0-98923-815-1 |accessdate=February 2, 2017 |via=trekkiefeminist.tumblr.com}}</ref> writing [[Westerns on television|Westerns]], furnishing scripts for ''[[Dick Powell's Zane Grey Theatre]]'' (1960), ''[[The Rebel (TV series)|The Rebel]]'' (1961), ''[[Lawman (TV series)|Lawman]]'' (1960–62), ''[[The Tall Man (TV series)|The Tall Man]]'' (1962), ''[[The Rifleman]]'' (1960–63) and ''[[The Big Valley]]'' (1965–69) during the 1960s.
She was also responsible for three episodes of the original ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' series, writing "[[The Gamesters of Triskelion]]" and "[[The Paradise Syndrome]]" (both 1968), and provided the final [[teleplay]] for "[[The Cloud Minders]]" (1969). She later wrote two episodes of ''[[Star Trek: The Animated Series]]'' ("[[The Lorelei Signal]]" and "[[The Ambergris Element]]", both 1973). Armen also co-wrote (with Alfred Harris) "The Savage Syndrome", an episode of the cancelled series ''[[Star Trek: Phase II]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/star-trek-10-unfilmed-episodes/ |title=Star Trek: 10 Unfilmed Episodes |first=Ed |last=Gross |date=April 7, 2016 |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |accessdate=February 2, 2017}}</ref>
During the 1970s, she also wrote episodes for the detective series ''[[Ironside (1967 TV series)|Ironside]]'' (1973), ''[[Cannon (TV series)|Cannon]]'' (1975), ''[[Baretta]]'' (1977) and ''[[Barnaby Jones]]'' (1977, 1978), as well as the science fiction series ''[[The Six Million Dollar Man]]'' (1975), ''[[Land of the Lost (1974 TV series)|Land of the Lost]]'' (1974, 1975), ''[[The Bionic Woman]]'' (1978) and ''[[Jason of Star Command]]'' (1979).
In the early 1980s, she wrote episodes of ''[[Fantasy Island]]'' (1981), ''[[Flamingo Road (TV series)|Flamingo Road]]'' (1981) and ''[[Emerald Point N.A.S.]]'' (1983). Although primarily a writer for episodic television, she wrote the television movie ''The New Daughters of Joshua Cabe'' (1976) for the series ''[[ABC Movie of the Week]]''. Armen ceased writing for television in 1983, publishing the western novel ''The Hanging of Father Miguel'' in 1984.<ref name="latimesObit">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/nov/20/local/me-passings20.1 |title=Margaret Armen, 82; One of First Successful Female TV Writers |date=November 20, 2003 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 2, 2017}}</ref>
Armen was a member of [[Western Writers of America]] from 1968,<ref name="cowboydirectory"/> and also served on the board of governors of the [[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|Television Academy]] for two years from 1970, and on the board of directors of the [[Writers Guild of America, West]], for three years from 1975.<ref name="cowboydirectory"/><ref name="latimesObit"/>
Armen died of [[heart failure]] in 2003 at her home in [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]],<ref name="latimesObit"/> and is buried at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park, Hollywood Hills]].<ref name="ObitNotice"/>
