{{Italic title}}[[File:Voltaire Precis title page.jpg|thumb|Title page of a first edition, from the collection of the Voltaire Foundation in Oxford]]'''''Précis du siècle de Louis XV''''' (''Short history of  the Age of Louis XV'') is a historical work by the French philosopher and author [[Voltaire]], first published in its own right 1768.<ref name="Pearson">{{cite book|last1=Pearson|first1=Roger|title=Voltaire almighty: a life in pursuit of freedom|date=2005|publisher=Bloomsbury|location=New York|isbn=9781582346304|page=305|edition=1., U.S.}}</ref> Celebrating the progress of [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] ideas and the retreat of [[prejudice]], it comments on cultural, economic and technological progress made in France during the reign of [[Louis XV of France]].<ref name="Pearson"/>

== Background ==
The material for the ''Précis'' had been previously been part of a history that Voltaire spent twenty years working on and which included ''[[Essai sur les mœurs et l'esprit des nations]]'' (''Essay on the customs and spirit of the nations'') and ''[[The Age of Louis XIV]]''. The ''Precis'' was introduced in 1762 as an appendix within this larger work, but later published separately.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OXXlCgQR4V8C|title=The Age of Voltaire: The Story of Civilization|last=Durant|first=Will|last2=Durant|first2=Ariel|date=2011|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9781451647662|page=800|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voltairefoundation.wordpress.com/2015/05/11/battles-on-and-off-the-field/|title=Battles on and off the field|last=|date=2015-05-11|website=Voltaire Foundation|access-date=2016-06-09}}</ref>

== Content ==
Voltaire comments on the trial of [[Thomas Arthur, comte de Lally]]; a case he had been following closely. Lally had been a successful military officer, and personally known to Voltaire. When Lally was involved at a military defeat, relinquishing the Indian town of [[Pondicherry]] to the English, his fellow officers blamed him. On his return to France, Lally was imprisoned without charge, put on trial in which he was denied a lawyer, and finally executed.<ref name="davidson"/> In his account of the case, Voltaire wrote, "His character made him detested by all who had to do with him. But that is not a reason for cutting off a man's head. The briefs both for and against him, which I have read attentively, contain nothing but insults, and not the least proof."<ref name="davidson">{{cite book|last1=Davidson|first1=Ian|title=Voltaire in Exile|date=2004|publisher=Atlantic books|isbn=1843540878|pages=159–164}}</ref>

The ''Precis'' also praises the courage of the Corsicans in defending against the French at the [[Battle of Ponte Novu]]. Voltaire writes:
<blockquote>The principal weapon of the Corsicans was their courage. This courage was so great that in one of these battles, near a river named Golo, they made a rampart of their dead in order to have the time to reload behind them before making a necessary retreat […] Bravery is found everywhere, but such actions aren’t seen except among free people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historytoday.com/sebastien-r-le-morillon/rethinking-napoleon%E2%80%99s-roots|title=Rethinking Napoleon’s Roots|last=Le Morillon|first=Sebastien R.|date=30 November 2015|website=History Today|publisher=|access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref></blockquote>

